ation of Criminals in Late Victorian and Edwardian Britain / rJoseph, Anne M. -- t10. Fingerprinting and the Argentine Plan for Universal Identification in the Late Nineteenth and Early Twentieth Centuries / rRuggiero, Kristin -- tPART THREE: IDENTIFICATION AND CONTROL OF MOVEMENT -- t11. Domenica Saba Takes to the Road: Origins and Development of a Modern Passport System in Lombardy-Veneto / rGeselle, Andrea -- t12. Governments and Forgers: Passports in Nineteenth-Century Europe / rFahrmeir, Andreas -- t13. A Many-Headed Monster: The Evolution of the Passport System in the Netherlands and Germany in the Long Nineteenth Century / rLucassen, Leo -- t14. The Great War and the Birth of the Modern Passport System / rTorpey, John -- tPART FOUR: CONTEMPORARY ISSUES IN IDENTIFICATION -- t15. DNA-Typing: Galton's Eugenic Dream Realized? / rSankar, Pamela -- t16. Under My Skin: From Identification Papers to Body Surveillance / rLyon, David -- t17. Identity and Anonymity: Some Conceptual Distinctions and Issues for Research / rMarx, Gary T. -- t18. Identifiying Unauthorized Foreign Workers in the German Labor Market / rVogel, Dita -- t19. Identity Cards, Ethnic Self-Perception, and Genocide in Rwanda / rLongman, Timothy -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex  aThis book addresses one of the least studied yet most pervasive aspects of modern life--the techniques and mechanisms by which official agencies certify individual identity. From passports and identity cards to labor registration and alien documentation, from fingerprinting to much-debated contemporary issues such as DNA-typing, body surveillance, and the catastrophic results of colonial-era identity documentation in postcolonial Rwanda, Documenting Individual Identity offers the most comprehensive historical overview of this fascinating topic ever published. The nineteen essays in this volume represent the collaborative effort of historians, sociologists, historians of science, political scientists, economists, and specialists in international relations. Together they cover a period from the emergence of systematic practices of written identification in early modern Europe through to the present day, and a geographic range that includes Europe, the Soviet Union, North and South America, and Africa. While the book is attuned to the nefarious possibilities of states' increasing capacity to identify individuals, it recognizes that these same techniques also certify citizens' eligibility for significant positive rights, such as welfare benefits and voting. Unprecedented in subject and scope, Documenting Individual Identity promises to shape a whole new field of research that crosses disciplinary boundaries and is of broad public and academic significance. In addition to the editors, the contributors are Valentin Groebner, Gérard Noiriel, Charles Steinwedel, Marc Garcelon, Jon Agar, Martine Kaluszynski, Peter Becker, Anne Joseph, Kristin Ruggiero, Andrea Geselle, Andreas Fahrmeier, Leo Lucassen, Pamela Sankar, David Lyon, Gary Marx, Dita Vogel, and Timothy Longman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aIdentificationxHistory. 0aPassportsxHistory. 0aStatus (Law)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aCaplan, Jane, eeditor.1 aTorpey, John, eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186856zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186856.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN